00:05:26.850 --> 00:05:31.320
OK, good.

00:05:42.060 --> 00:05:42.700
All right.

00:06:04.450 --> 00:06:11.240
Let me just summarize what our
current discussion is about.

00:06:11.240 --> 00:06:14.660
This section is called
Quantum Metrology.

00:06:14.660 --> 00:06:18.690
It is a section where we want
to apply the concepts we have

00:06:18.690 --> 00:06:22.300
learned to precision
measurements.

00:06:22.300 --> 00:06:26.080
It's actually a chapter
which I find nice.

00:06:26.080 --> 00:06:28.640
We're not really
introducing new concepts.

00:06:28.640 --> 00:06:31.270
We're using concepts
previously introduced.

00:06:31.270 --> 00:06:33.490
And now you see how
powerful those concepts

00:06:33.490 --> 00:06:36.790
are, what they can be used for.

00:06:36.790 --> 00:06:42.600
So we want to
discuss the precision

00:06:42.600 --> 00:06:45.050
we can obtain in
quantum measurement.

00:06:45.050 --> 00:06:48.490
We apply it here to an
atom in the interferometer,

00:06:48.490 --> 00:06:50.900
to an optical interferometer.

00:06:50.900 --> 00:06:53.190
We could also
discuss the precision

00:06:53.190 --> 00:06:54.920
of spectroscopic measurements.

00:06:54.920 --> 00:06:59.280
A lot of precision measurements
have many things in common.

00:06:59.280 --> 00:07:01.960
So what we discuss here
is as a generic example

00:07:01.960 --> 00:07:04.710
for precision measurement
that we send light

00:07:04.710 --> 00:07:06.580
from our center interferometer.

00:07:06.580 --> 00:07:07.760
Here is a phase shift.

00:07:07.760 --> 00:07:10.120
And the question is,
how accurately can we

00:07:10.120 --> 00:07:15.442
measure the phase shift when
we use n photons as a resource?

00:07:15.442 --> 00:07:16.900
And of course, you
are all familiar

00:07:16.900 --> 00:07:22.600
with the fundamental limit of
standard measurements, which

00:07:22.600 --> 00:07:24.180
is short noise.

00:07:24.180 --> 00:07:28.430
And sort of as a warm up in
our last class Wednesday,

00:07:28.430 --> 00:07:39.280
week ago, I showed you that when
we use coherent states of light

00:07:39.280 --> 00:07:41.350
at the input of
the interferometer,

00:07:41.350 --> 00:07:45.080
we obtain the short noise.

00:07:45.080 --> 00:07:48.130
Well, it may not be surprising,
because coherent light

00:07:48.130 --> 00:07:53.900
is as close as possible, has
similar to classical light.

00:07:53.900 --> 00:07:58.270
But then we discussed single
mode, single photon input.

00:07:58.270 --> 00:08:06.240
And by using the formalism
of the Mach-Zehnder

00:08:06.240 --> 00:08:10.190
interferometer, we've found that
the phase uncertainty is again

00:08:10.190 --> 00:08:13.920
1 over square root n.

00:08:13.920 --> 00:08:19.080
So then the question is, how can
we go to the Heisenberg limit,

00:08:19.080 --> 00:08:24.120
where we have an uncertainty
in the phase of 1 over n?

00:08:24.120 --> 00:08:27.910
And just as a reminder,
I find it very helpful.

00:08:27.910 --> 00:08:35.230
I told you that you can always
envision if you have n photons

00:08:35.230 --> 00:08:39.840
and you multiply it, put
the n photons together

00:08:39.840 --> 00:08:43.669
by multiplying the
frequency by n,

00:08:43.669 --> 00:08:45.960
then you have one photon
which [INAUDIBLE] with n times

00:08:45.960 --> 00:08:47.390
the frequency.

00:08:47.390 --> 00:08:49.550
And it's clear if you
do a measurement at n

00:08:49.550 --> 00:08:52.100
times the frequency,
your precision in phase

00:08:52.100 --> 00:08:54.700
is n times better.

00:08:54.700 --> 00:08:57.970
So what we have to do is
we have to sort of put

00:08:57.970 --> 00:09:00.130
the n photons together.

00:09:00.130 --> 00:09:03.150
And then we can get a precision
of the measurement, which

00:09:03.150 --> 00:09:06.680
is not square root n,
but n times better.

00:09:06.680 --> 00:09:08.460
So this is what we
want to continue today.

00:09:12.840 --> 00:09:16.330
This is the outline I gave
you in the last class.

00:09:16.330 --> 00:09:19.620
If you have this
optical interferometer,

00:09:19.620 --> 00:09:21.520
this Mach-Zehnder
interferometer.

00:09:21.520 --> 00:09:24.050
And if you use coherent
sets or single photons

00:09:24.050 --> 00:09:27.020
as the input state, we
obtain the short noise.

00:09:27.020 --> 00:09:29.150
Now we have to change something.

00:09:29.150 --> 00:09:31.570
And we can change
the input state,

00:09:31.570 --> 00:09:35.410
we can change the beam splitter,
or we can change the readout.

00:09:35.410 --> 00:09:38.780
So we have to change something
where we entangle the n

00:09:38.780 --> 00:09:44.190
photons, make sure in some sense
they act as one giant photons,

00:09:44.190 --> 00:09:46.800
with either n times
the frequency,

00:09:46.800 --> 00:09:53.010
but definitely with n times
the sensitivity to phase shift.

00:09:53.010 --> 00:09:54.050
Any questions?

00:09:58.661 --> 00:09:59.160
Good.

00:09:59.160 --> 00:10:04.040
The first example, which
we pretty much covered

00:10:04.040 --> 00:10:08.740
in the last class, was an
entangled state interferometer.

00:10:08.740 --> 00:10:12.100
So instead of having the
Mach-Zehnder interferometer

00:10:12.100 --> 00:10:16.760
as we had before, we have
sort of a Bell state creation

00:10:16.760 --> 00:10:17.700
device.

00:10:17.700 --> 00:10:19.860
Then we provide the phase shift.

00:10:19.860 --> 00:10:23.610
And then we have a
Bell analysis device.

00:10:23.610 --> 00:10:30.590
And I want to use here the
formalism and the symbols

00:10:30.590 --> 00:10:32.770
we had introduced earlier.

00:10:32.770 --> 00:10:40.090
So just as a reminder, what
we need is I need two gates.

00:10:40.090 --> 00:10:46.860
One is the Hadamard gate,
which in matrix representation

00:10:46.860 --> 00:10:49.620
has this matrix form.

00:10:49.620 --> 00:10:53.590
And that means if you have
a qubit which is either up

00:10:53.590 --> 00:10:55.840
or down and you apply
the matrix to it,

00:10:55.840 --> 00:10:58.890
you put it in a superposition
state of up and down.

00:10:58.890 --> 00:11:01.050
It's a single qubit rotation.

00:11:01.050 --> 00:11:03.720
You can say for the bloch
on the Bloch sphere,

00:11:03.720 --> 00:11:04.850
it's a 90 degree rotation.

00:11:07.820 --> 00:11:11.290
The second gate we need
is the controlled NOT.

00:11:14.250 --> 00:11:18.700
And the controlled NOT
we discussed previously

00:11:18.700 --> 00:11:23.850
can be implemented by
having an interferometer

00:11:23.850 --> 00:11:31.160
and using a non-linear Kerr
medium coupling another photon

00:11:31.160 --> 00:11:33.510
to the interferometer
in such a way

00:11:33.510 --> 00:11:35.710
that if you have a
photon in mode C,

00:11:35.710 --> 00:11:38.280
it creates a phase shift
with the interferometer.

00:11:38.280 --> 00:11:41.190
If there is no
photon in mode C, it

00:11:41.190 --> 00:11:44.350
does not create an
additional phase shift.

00:11:44.350 --> 00:11:46.940
And as we have
discussed, this can

00:11:46.940 --> 00:11:48.695
implement the controlled NOT.

00:11:51.700 --> 00:11:54.220
So these are the ingredients.

00:11:54.220 --> 00:11:57.460
And at the end of
the last class,

00:11:57.460 --> 00:12:03.450
I just showed you what those
quantum gates can do for us.

00:12:03.450 --> 00:12:08.390
If you have two qubits at
the input, we apply the--

00:12:08.390 --> 00:12:11.980
and I will assume they
are both in logical 0--

00:12:11.980 --> 00:12:16.390
the Hadamard gate makes
the coherent superposition.

00:12:16.390 --> 00:12:18.490
And then, we have
a controlled NOT

00:12:18.490 --> 00:12:20.900
where this is the target gate.

00:12:20.900 --> 00:12:25.960
Well, if this is 0, if
the control beat is 0,

00:12:25.960 --> 00:12:27.990
the target beat stays 0.

00:12:27.990 --> 00:12:29.960
So we get 0, 0.

00:12:29.960 --> 00:12:33.550
If the control beat is 1, the
target beat is flipped to 1.

00:12:33.550 --> 00:12:35.600
So we get 1, 1.

00:12:35.600 --> 00:12:37.250
So the result is
that we have now

00:12:37.250 --> 00:12:41.060
created a state 0, 0 plus 1, 1.

00:12:41.060 --> 00:12:44.760
And if we apply a phase shift
to all the photons coming out

00:12:44.760 --> 00:12:50.050
on the right hand side, we get
a phase shift which is too fine.

00:12:50.050 --> 00:12:51.720
So we already get the idea.

00:12:51.720 --> 00:12:54.850
If we take advantage
of a state 1, 1,

00:12:54.850 --> 00:12:58.880
it has twice the [? face ?]
sensitivity as a single photon.

00:12:58.880 --> 00:13:01.360
And we may therefore
get the full benefit

00:13:01.360 --> 00:13:04.580
of the factor of 2, and
not just square root 2.

00:13:04.580 --> 00:13:06.330
And this is what this
discussion is about.

00:13:08.947 --> 00:13:09.446
Questions?

00:13:13.200 --> 00:13:14.595
OK, so that's where we ended.

00:13:17.200 --> 00:13:26.650
We can now use
another controlled NOT

00:13:26.650 --> 00:13:28.255
and bring in the third qubit.

00:13:39.050 --> 00:13:44.240
So what we create here.

00:13:46.750 --> 00:13:50.200
Just make a reference, this
is where we start today.

00:13:53.280 --> 00:13:59.900
So we create here the state,
which is either all beats

00:13:59.900 --> 00:14:13.260
are 0, all beats are 1, and
then the phase shift gives us

00:14:13.260 --> 00:14:17.280
three times the phase shift phi.

00:14:17.280 --> 00:14:23.010
And therefore, by bringing
in more and more qubits,

00:14:23.010 --> 00:14:25.770
I've shown you n equals
1, n equals 2, n equals 3.

00:14:25.770 --> 00:14:27.650
So now you can go to n.

00:14:27.650 --> 00:14:34.740
We obtain states which have n
times the phase sensitivity.

00:14:43.690 --> 00:14:50.800
Let me just mention in
passing that for n equals 3,

00:14:50.800 --> 00:14:58.000
the superposition of 0, 0, 0
and 1, 1, 1 goes by the name

00:14:58.000 --> 00:15:01.710
not gigahertz, GHZ.

00:15:01.710 --> 00:15:02.210
Greenberger.

00:15:05.950 --> 00:15:07.180
This third one is Zeilinger.

00:15:07.180 --> 00:15:08.220
The second one is--

00:15:08.220 --> 00:15:08.887
AUDIENCE: Horne.

00:15:08.887 --> 00:15:09.594
PROFESSOR: Horne.

00:15:09.594 --> 00:15:10.260
Thank you.

00:15:10.260 --> 00:15:13.460
Greenberger-Horne-Zeilinger
state.

00:15:13.460 --> 00:15:15.600
And those states play
an important role

00:15:15.600 --> 00:15:18.120
in test of Bell's inequality.

00:15:18.120 --> 00:15:30.400
Or more generally, states which
are macroscopically distinct

00:15:30.400 --> 00:15:34.270
are also regarded cat states
or Schrodinger cat states.

00:15:42.620 --> 00:15:48.170
If we apply a phase
shift and go now

00:15:48.170 --> 00:15:50.920
through the
entangler in reverse,

00:15:50.920 --> 00:15:55.770
just a reverse sequence of
CNOT gates and Hadamard gates,

00:15:55.770 --> 00:16:03.010
then we have all
the other n minus,

00:16:03.010 --> 00:16:04.960
have the n minus 1 qubits.

00:16:04.960 --> 00:16:09.460
All the qubits except
for the first reset to 0.

00:16:09.460 --> 00:16:12.680
But the first qubit is now
in a superposition state

00:16:12.680 --> 00:16:15.850
where we have the
phase into the power n.

00:16:19.970 --> 00:16:22.460
And now, we can
make a measurement.

00:16:22.460 --> 00:16:27.110
And P is now the probability
to find a single photon

00:16:27.110 --> 00:16:29.150
in the first qubit.

00:16:29.150 --> 00:16:30.790
So in other words,
our measurement

00:16:30.790 --> 00:16:33.895
is exactly the same
as we had before where

00:16:33.895 --> 00:16:36.230
we had the normal
Mach-Zehnder interferometer.

00:16:36.230 --> 00:16:38.080
We put in one photon at a time.

00:16:38.080 --> 00:16:39.940
And we determined
the probability.

00:16:39.940 --> 00:16:46.150
What is the photon at one of the
outputs of the interferometer?

00:16:46.150 --> 00:16:49.620
But the only
difference is that we

00:16:49.620 --> 00:16:54.820
have now a factor of n in the
exponent for the phase shift.

00:16:54.820 --> 00:17:00.340
And I want to show you what
is caused by this factor of n.

00:17:04.380 --> 00:17:07.810
Let me first remind
you how we analyzed

00:17:07.810 --> 00:17:11.950
the sensitivity of
an interferometer

00:17:11.950 --> 00:17:14.349
for single photon input before.

00:17:14.349 --> 00:17:19.630
So for a moment,
set n equals 1 now.

00:17:19.630 --> 00:17:23.010
Then you get what we
discussed two weeks ago.

00:17:23.010 --> 00:17:26.349
The probability is [INAUDIBLE]
as an interferometer.

00:17:26.349 --> 00:17:31.320
Sine also, cosine also
infringes with cosine phi.

00:17:31.320 --> 00:17:34.140
If you do measurements
with a probability P,

00:17:34.140 --> 00:17:37.115
that's a binomial distribution.

00:17:37.115 --> 00:17:38.700
Then the deviation
or the square root

00:17:38.700 --> 00:17:41.890
of the variance in the binomial
distribution is P times 1

00:17:41.890 --> 00:17:49.300
minus P. And by inserting p
here, we get sine phi over 2.

00:17:49.300 --> 00:17:54.250
The derivative of P, which
is our signal, with a phase

00:17:54.250 --> 00:17:56.300
is given by that.

00:17:56.300 --> 00:17:58.590
And then just using
error propagation,

00:17:58.590 --> 00:18:01.200
the uncertainty in the
phase is the uncertainty

00:18:01.200 --> 00:18:03.670
in P divided by dp dt.

00:18:07.310 --> 00:18:11.280
So then we repeat the
whole experiment n times,

00:18:11.280 --> 00:18:15.350
and if your binomial
distribution and we

00:18:15.350 --> 00:18:19.520
do m [INAUDIBLE] of our
[INAUDIBLE] with probability P,

00:18:19.520 --> 00:18:21.630
we get an m under
the square root.

00:18:21.630 --> 00:18:24.040
And then we get 1
over square root m.

00:18:24.040 --> 00:18:26.354
And this was what I
showed you two weeks ago,

00:18:26.354 --> 00:18:27.645
the standard short noise limit.

00:18:30.670 --> 00:18:35.590
But now we have this
additional factor of n

00:18:35.590 --> 00:18:46.270
here, which means that
our probability has

00:18:46.270 --> 00:18:51.600
a cosine which goes with n phi.

00:18:51.600 --> 00:18:56.920
When we take the derivative,
we get a factor of n here.

00:18:56.920 --> 00:19:02.990
And then dp d phi
has the derivative.

00:19:02.990 --> 00:19:05.570
But then we have to
use a chain rule, which

00:19:05.570 --> 00:19:08.360
has another factor of n.

00:19:08.360 --> 00:19:13.220
And therefore, we obtain now
that the phase sensitivity

00:19:13.220 --> 00:19:14.805
goes as 1 over n.

00:19:18.610 --> 00:19:21.320
And therefore, we reach
the Heisenberg limit.

00:19:21.320 --> 00:19:26.400
So if you have now your n
photon entangler, the one I

00:19:26.400 --> 00:19:31.930
just-- the entanglement
operation with these n cubits

00:19:31.930 --> 00:19:36.760
is special beam spreader
replaced by the entangler,

00:19:36.760 --> 00:19:40.681
we have now a sensitivity,
which goes 1 over n.

00:19:40.681 --> 00:19:42.180
And then of course,
if you want, you

00:19:42.180 --> 00:19:44.100
can repeat the
experiment n times.

00:19:44.100 --> 00:19:45.950
And whenever you
repeat an experiment,

00:19:45.950 --> 00:19:49.254
you gain an addition with
the square root of m.

00:20:01.980 --> 00:20:03.400
Just give me one second.

00:20:03.400 --> 00:20:04.185
We have this.

00:20:07.420 --> 00:20:17.470
OK, so this is an example where
we had n qubits entangled,

00:20:17.470 --> 00:20:18.570
like here.

00:20:18.570 --> 00:20:22.720
And the sensitivity of
this interferometer scales

00:20:22.720 --> 00:20:26.070
now as the Heisenberg
limit with 1 over n.

00:20:31.810 --> 00:20:36.669
OK, I want to give you,
because they're all nice

00:20:36.669 --> 00:20:38.460
and they're all special,
I want to give you

00:20:38.460 --> 00:20:41.840
three more example how you can
reach the Heisenberg limit.

00:20:46.330 --> 00:20:52.300
The next one goes by the name
super beam splitter method.

00:20:52.300 --> 00:20:56.230
It's actually a very
fancy beam splitter

00:20:56.230 --> 00:20:59.680
where you have two prods
of your beam splitter.

00:20:59.680 --> 00:21:03.160
One has 0 and one has n photons.

00:21:03.160 --> 00:21:07.190
And behind the beam splitter,
you have two options.

00:21:07.190 --> 00:21:09.950
Either all the n photons
are in one state,

00:21:09.950 --> 00:21:12.970
or the n photons are
in the other state.

00:21:12.970 --> 00:21:16.900
You never have
any other mixture.

00:21:16.900 --> 00:21:18.990
Of course, you know your
standard half silvered

00:21:18.990 --> 00:21:24.440
mirror will not do that for
you, because it will split the n

00:21:24.440 --> 00:21:27.650
photon state with some
Poissonian statistics

00:21:27.650 --> 00:21:30.290
or whatnot into the
two arms and such.

00:21:30.290 --> 00:21:32.410
And you can calculate
exactly what a normal beam

00:21:32.410 --> 00:21:33.450
splitter does to that.

00:21:33.450 --> 00:21:35.040
It's very, very different.

00:21:35.040 --> 00:21:38.152
This here is a very, very
special beam splitter.

00:21:42.580 --> 00:21:47.070
Just to demystify this
beam splitter a little bit,

00:21:47.070 --> 00:21:56.660
I want to show you that, at
least conceptually, there

00:21:56.660 --> 00:22:00.550
is an easy implementation
with atoms.

00:22:00.550 --> 00:22:03.500
I really like in this section
to grab an example from atoms

00:22:03.500 --> 00:22:06.720
and to grab an example for
photons, because it really

00:22:06.720 --> 00:22:10.090
brings out that the
language may develop equally

00:22:10.090 --> 00:22:12.360
applies to atoms and photon.

00:22:12.360 --> 00:22:14.980
So if I take now
an easy example,

00:22:14.980 --> 00:22:17.790
if I take an example of the
Bose-Einstein condensate with n

00:22:17.790 --> 00:22:22.740
atoms, let's assume
we have a double well.

00:22:22.740 --> 00:22:24.950
But now we have
attractive interactions.

00:22:29.220 --> 00:22:31.050
This is not your standard BEC.

00:22:31.050 --> 00:22:33.130
Your standard
Bose-Einstein condensate

00:22:33.130 --> 00:22:36.840
has repulsive interaction,
with attractive interaction.

00:22:36.840 --> 00:22:40.740
If you go beyond a certain
size, certain a atom number,

00:22:40.740 --> 00:22:42.350
the condensate will collapse.

00:22:42.350 --> 00:22:45.190
So let's assume we have a
Bose-Einstein condensate with n

00:22:45.190 --> 00:22:45.900
atoms.

00:22:45.900 --> 00:22:47.940
There are some
attractive interactions,

00:22:47.940 --> 00:22:51.090
but we stay within
the stability diagram

00:22:51.090 --> 00:22:57.115
that those atoms do not-- that
those atoms do not collapse.

00:23:00.640 --> 00:23:03.900
So now, if the atoms
are attractive,

00:23:03.900 --> 00:23:05.280
they all want to be together.

00:23:05.280 --> 00:23:08.700
Because then they lower
the energy of each other.

00:23:08.700 --> 00:23:10.940
So if you have something
with attractive interaction,

00:23:10.940 --> 00:23:13.210
you want to have
n atoms together.

00:23:15.780 --> 00:23:21.390
But if your double
well potential

00:23:21.390 --> 00:23:28.990
is absolutely symmetric,
there is no symmetry breaking,

00:23:28.990 --> 00:23:32.480
and you have an equal
amplitude for all the atoms

00:23:32.480 --> 00:23:33.703
to be in the other well.

00:23:37.760 --> 00:23:46.020
So therefore, under the
very idealized situation

00:23:46.020 --> 00:23:48.410
I described here,
you will actually

00:23:48.410 --> 00:23:51.990
create a superposition
state of n atoms

00:23:51.990 --> 00:23:55.770
in one well with n
atoms in the other well.

00:23:55.770 --> 00:23:57.790
And this is exactly
what we tried

00:23:57.790 --> 00:23:59.690
to accomplish with
this beam splitter.

00:24:11.430 --> 00:24:17.690
OK, so if we have this
special beam splitter, which

00:24:17.690 --> 00:24:21.070
creates that state,
then when we add a phase

00:24:21.070 --> 00:24:25.680
shift to one arm of
the interferometer,

00:24:25.680 --> 00:24:31.860
we obtain-- which looks very
promising-- a phase shift

00:24:31.860 --> 00:24:33.800
phi multiplied by n.

00:24:38.120 --> 00:24:57.050
And if we read it
out, we have now

00:24:57.050 --> 00:25:04.850
if you pass it through the
other super beam splitter,

00:25:04.850 --> 00:25:10.460
we create again a
superposition of n0 and 0n.

00:25:14.390 --> 00:25:18.520
But now, because
of the phase shift

00:25:18.520 --> 00:25:23.280
with cosine and sine factors,
which involve n times

00:25:23.280 --> 00:25:24.150
the phase shift.

00:25:30.020 --> 00:25:33.080
For obvious reasons,
those states

00:25:33.080 --> 00:25:37.420
also go by the name noon states.

00:25:37.420 --> 00:25:39.940
That's the name which everybody
uses for those states,

00:25:39.940 --> 00:25:44.410
because if you just read
n00n, it gives noon.

00:25:44.410 --> 00:25:48.440
So this is the
famous noon state.

00:25:48.440 --> 00:25:51.880
So it seems it smells
already, right,

00:25:51.880 --> 00:25:55.040
because it has a
phase shift of n phi.

00:25:55.040 --> 00:26:00.720
Let me just convince you
that this is indeed the case.

00:26:00.720 --> 00:26:11.680
So the probability
of reading out

00:26:11.680 --> 00:26:15.730
0 photons in one arm
of the interferometer

00:26:15.730 --> 00:26:19.440
scales now with
the cosine square.

00:26:22.340 --> 00:26:27.810
If you do one
single measurement,

00:26:27.810 --> 00:26:40.860
the binomial
distribution is the same

00:26:40.860 --> 00:26:43.170
as before, but
with a factor of n.

00:26:47.310 --> 00:26:54.520
The derivative has
those factors of n.

00:26:54.520 --> 00:27:06.970
And that means that the variance
in the phase measurement

00:27:06.970 --> 00:27:08.080
is now 1 over n.

00:27:14.180 --> 00:27:17.950
If you want a reference,
I put it down here.

00:27:17.950 --> 00:27:20.260
As far as I know,
the experiment has

00:27:20.260 --> 00:27:22.680
been done with three
photons, but not

00:27:22.680 --> 00:27:23.840
with larger photon number.

00:27:32.306 --> 00:27:33.302
Questions?

