00:28:34.480 --> 00:28:36.739
And how to make it
experimentally [INAUDIBLE],

00:28:36.739 --> 00:28:38.030
this is a really big challenge.

00:28:40.626 --> 00:28:41.125
[? Tino ?].

00:28:41.125 --> 00:28:42.740
AUDIENCE: I have a question.

00:28:42.740 --> 00:28:45.190
Let's say we're somehow
able to make the double well

00:28:45.190 --> 00:28:46.660
potential perfect.

00:28:46.660 --> 00:28:49.110
But if we didn't have
attractive interactions,

00:28:49.110 --> 00:28:51.720
then wouldn't he just
get a big product state

00:28:51.720 --> 00:28:54.310
of each atom being
in either well?

00:28:57.540 --> 00:29:00.414
PROFESSOR: OK, if you're
a non-interacting system,

00:29:00.414 --> 00:29:02.205
the ground state of a
double well potential

00:29:02.205 --> 00:29:06.990
is just your metric state 1
plus 2 over square root 2.

00:29:06.990 --> 00:29:09.920
And for non-interactive
BEC, you figure out

00:29:09.920 --> 00:29:11.900
what is the ground
state for one particle

00:29:11.900 --> 00:29:13.770
and then take it to the power n.

00:29:13.770 --> 00:29:15.106
This is the non-interactive BEC.

00:29:15.106 --> 00:29:17.605
STUDENT: So then entanglement
is because of the interaction,

00:29:17.605 --> 00:29:18.490
right?

00:29:18.490 --> 00:29:21.590
PROFESSOR: If you have
strong repulsive interaction,

00:29:21.590 --> 00:29:23.620
you have something
which should remind you

00:29:23.620 --> 00:29:25.900
of the [INAUDIBLE] insulator.

00:29:25.900 --> 00:29:27.110
You have n atoms.

00:29:27.110 --> 00:29:30.310
And n over 2 atoms go
to one well. n over 2 go

00:29:30.310 --> 00:29:31.840
to the other well.

00:29:31.840 --> 00:29:35.850
Because any form of number
fluctuations would be costly.

00:29:35.850 --> 00:29:38.400
It will cost you additional
repulsive interaction.

00:29:38.400 --> 00:29:40.460
So therefore, the
condensate wants

00:29:40.460 --> 00:29:43.640
to break up into
two equal parts.

00:29:43.640 --> 00:29:45.260
So that's actually
a way how you would

00:29:45.260 --> 00:29:48.650
create another non-classical
state, the dual flux

00:29:48.650 --> 00:29:51.690
state of n over 2,
n over 2 particle.

00:29:51.690 --> 00:29:58.140
And for attractive
interactions, well you

00:29:58.140 --> 00:29:59.540
should create the known state.

00:30:05.510 --> 00:30:09.340
OK, so this was now
a state n0 and 0n.

00:30:12.610 --> 00:30:16.410
There is another
state, which you

00:30:16.410 --> 00:30:19.530
have encountered
in your homework.

00:30:19.530 --> 00:30:25.350
And this is a superposition
not of n0 and 0n and n0.

00:30:25.350 --> 00:30:30.670
It's a superposition of n
minus 1n and n n minus 1.

00:30:30.670 --> 00:30:34.660
This state goes by the person
I think who invented it,

00:30:34.660 --> 00:30:36.560
the [? Yerkey ?] state.

00:30:36.560 --> 00:30:41.190
And you showed in your homework
that with that, you also

00:30:41.190 --> 00:30:45.260
reach Heisenberg Limited
Interferometry, where

00:30:45.260 --> 00:30:49.150
the phase scales is 1 over n.

00:30:49.150 --> 00:30:53.820
What I want to add
here to it is how

00:30:53.820 --> 00:30:56.560
one can create such
a [? Yerkey ?] state.

00:30:56.560 --> 00:30:59.960
And again, I want
to use the example

00:30:59.960 --> 00:31:02.800
with an atomic
Bose-Einstein condensate.

00:31:02.800 --> 00:31:06.135
And here's the reference where
this was very nicely discussed.

00:31:11.660 --> 00:31:16.420
So let's assume we can create
two Bose-Einstein condensates.

00:31:16.420 --> 00:31:19.300
And they have exactly n atoms.

00:31:19.300 --> 00:31:22.330
And I would actually refer
to [? Tino's ?] questions how

00:31:22.330 --> 00:31:30.050
to make them have
two n atoms in a trap

00:31:30.050 --> 00:31:32.310
and then make a
double well potential,

00:31:32.310 --> 00:31:35.250
deform the harmonic oscillator
potential to a double well

00:31:35.250 --> 00:31:36.260
potential.

00:31:36.260 --> 00:31:40.060
Then for strong
repulsive interactions,

00:31:40.060 --> 00:31:41.760
the condensate
will symmetrically

00:31:41.760 --> 00:31:47.580
split into two flux states,
each of which has n atoms.

00:31:47.580 --> 00:31:51.830
So now how can we create the
[? Yerkey ?] state from that?

00:31:51.830 --> 00:31:56.910
Well, we simply have--
we leak out atoms.

00:31:56.910 --> 00:31:59.980
We leak atoms out of the trap.

00:31:59.980 --> 00:32:03.640
My group demonstrated an RF
beam splitter, how you can just

00:32:03.640 --> 00:32:08.070
split in very
controlled way start

00:32:08.070 --> 00:32:11.810
rotating the cloud
on non-trapped state.

00:32:11.810 --> 00:32:14.970
And then atoms slowly leak out.

00:32:14.970 --> 00:32:17.240
Well, when you can
measure, of course,

00:32:17.240 --> 00:32:19.470
you can take an atom
detector and measure

00:32:19.470 --> 00:32:21.640
that an atom has
been out-coupled,

00:32:21.640 --> 00:32:26.065
that an atom has
leaked out of the trap.

00:32:26.065 --> 00:32:28.220
If you don't like
RF rotation, you

00:32:28.220 --> 00:32:31.810
can also think that there
is a tunneling barrier,

00:32:31.810 --> 00:32:35.240
and atoms slowly leak out
by whatever mechanism.

00:32:35.240 --> 00:32:38.290
And the moment you
detect that an atom,

00:32:38.290 --> 00:32:42.275
you then project the state in
the trap to n minus 1 atom,

00:32:42.275 --> 00:32:45.030
because you've measured
that one atom has come out.

00:32:45.030 --> 00:32:47.415
But now you use a beam splitter.

00:32:47.415 --> 00:32:51.610
And a beam splitter could
simply be a focused laser beam.

00:32:51.610 --> 00:32:54.030
And the atoms have
a 50% probability

00:32:54.030 --> 00:32:57.860
of being reflected or
end up tunneling through.

00:32:57.860 --> 00:33:01.250
So therefore, if you
have now a detector

00:33:01.250 --> 00:33:03.430
which measures the
atoms on one side

00:33:03.430 --> 00:33:08.470
and the atoms on the
other side, then you

00:33:08.470 --> 00:33:14.020
don't know anymore when the
detector makes click form which

00:33:14.020 --> 00:33:16.710
atom trap the atom came.

00:33:16.710 --> 00:33:20.260
Or more formally,
a beam splitter

00:33:20.260 --> 00:33:25.340
transforms the two input modes
ab into a plus b and a minus b

00:33:25.340 --> 00:33:27.790
normalized by square root 2.

00:33:27.790 --> 00:33:32.840
So therefore, if
this detector clicks,

00:33:32.840 --> 00:33:40.120
when you project the remaining
atoms into the symmetric state,

00:33:40.120 --> 00:33:44.840
here you detect one atom
in the mode a plus b.

00:33:44.840 --> 00:33:49.220
And that means that
the remaining atoms

00:33:49.220 --> 00:33:51.930
have been projected into
the [? Yerkey ?] state.

00:33:51.930 --> 00:33:54.070
If the lower atom
detector would click,

00:33:54.070 --> 00:33:56.600
well, you get a minus sign here.

00:33:56.600 --> 00:34:00.540
So that's one way how at
least in a conceptually simple

00:34:00.540 --> 00:34:05.120
situation, you can prepare
this highly non-classical state

00:34:05.120 --> 00:34:07.910
by starting with
a dual flux state

00:34:07.910 --> 00:34:11.480
of Bose-Einstein
condensates, and then using--

00:34:11.480 --> 00:34:16.050
and this is an ongoing theme
here-- by using a measurement,

00:34:16.050 --> 00:34:19.060
and then the
post-measurement state is

00:34:19.060 --> 00:34:21.469
the non-classical state
you wanted to prepare.

00:34:34.090 --> 00:34:34.830
Question?

00:34:34.830 --> 00:34:35.330
Yes.

00:34:35.330 --> 00:34:37.274
AUDIENCE: How can you
ensure that only one

00:34:37.274 --> 00:34:42.620
atom leaves the [INAUDIBLE]?

00:34:42.620 --> 00:34:44.650
PROFESSOR: The idea
is that we leak atoms

00:34:44.650 --> 00:34:46.870
out very, very slowly.

00:34:46.870 --> 00:34:48.989
And then we have
a detector, which

00:34:48.989 --> 00:34:52.090
we assume has 100%
quantum efficiency.

00:34:52.090 --> 00:34:55.820
So therefore, we simply wait
until the detector tells us

00:34:55.820 --> 00:34:58.060
that one atom has leaked out.

00:34:58.060 --> 00:35:02.050
And in an idealized experiment,
we know the atoms either

00:35:02.050 --> 00:35:03.791
have been measured
by the detector,

00:35:03.791 --> 00:35:05.040
or they are still in the trap.

00:35:07.781 --> 00:35:09.405
AUDIENCE: And also,
is there a property

00:35:09.405 --> 00:35:14.740
that holds the [INAUDIBLE]
you detect atoms [INAUDIBLE]?

00:35:18.150 --> 00:35:20.360
PROFESSOR: In principle
yes, but the idea here

00:35:20.360 --> 00:35:24.490
is if you have a very
slow leakage process,

00:35:24.490 --> 00:35:27.160
the probability that you detect
two atoms at the same time

00:35:27.160 --> 00:35:28.250
is really zero.

00:35:28.250 --> 00:35:31.270
You leak them continuously
and slowly, but then

00:35:31.270 --> 00:35:34.130
quantum mechanically, that
means for most of the time,

00:35:34.130 --> 00:35:34.970
you measure nothing.

00:35:34.970 --> 00:35:37.530
That means the leakage
hasn't taken place.

00:35:37.530 --> 00:35:40.430
The quantum mechanical
system has not developed yet.

00:35:40.430 --> 00:35:42.940
But the moment you
perform a measurement,

00:35:42.940 --> 00:35:45.040
you project-- it's
really the same

00:35:45.040 --> 00:35:47.680
if you say you have
n radioactive atoms.

00:35:47.680 --> 00:35:48.870
You have a detector.

00:35:48.870 --> 00:35:50.610
And when the
detector makes click,

00:35:50.610 --> 00:35:54.540
you know you have n minus
1 radioactive atoms left.

00:35:54.540 --> 00:35:57.900
It's just applied here
to two atom types.

00:35:57.900 --> 00:35:58.852
Other questions?

00:35:58.852 --> 00:35:59.768
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]?

00:36:02.522 --> 00:36:03.900
PROFESSOR: No.

00:36:03.900 --> 00:36:06.000
And maybe I'll tell
you now why not.

00:36:10.825 --> 00:36:14.080
We have discussed
the noon state.

00:36:14.080 --> 00:36:17.620
And we have discussed here
a highly non-classical

00:36:17.620 --> 00:36:19.970
superposition state.

00:36:19.970 --> 00:36:23.230
Let's just go back
to the noon state.

00:36:23.230 --> 00:36:28.060
We have n atoms here, zero here,
or n atoms, or the reverse.

00:36:28.060 --> 00:36:32.970
But now, assume a single atom
is lost, is lost from your trap

00:36:32.970 --> 00:36:35.230
by some background
gas collisions.

00:36:35.230 --> 00:36:39.880
And you have surrounded
the trap with a detector.

00:36:39.880 --> 00:36:43.540
So if you have the noon state,
the symmetric superposition

00:36:43.540 --> 00:36:46.030
state, all atoms here
and all atoms there.

00:36:46.030 --> 00:36:49.135
But by your background process,
by an inelastic collision,

00:36:49.135 --> 00:36:50.680
you lose one atom.

00:36:50.680 --> 00:36:51.950
And you detect it.

00:36:51.950 --> 00:36:53.705
You could set up your
detectors that you

00:36:53.705 --> 00:36:57.520
know from which
that you figure out

00:36:57.520 --> 00:36:59.900
from which trap was
the particle lost.

00:36:59.900 --> 00:37:03.000
So therefore, a
single particle lost

00:37:03.000 --> 00:37:07.080
if you localize from which
trap the particle is lost

00:37:07.080 --> 00:37:11.140
would immediately project
the noon state into a state

00:37:11.140 --> 00:37:15.670
where you know I have n or
n minus 1 atoms in one well,

00:37:15.670 --> 00:37:19.720
and 0 in the other well.

00:37:19.720 --> 00:37:23.510
So I've already told
you, with the attenuator,

00:37:23.510 --> 00:37:26.300
you can never assume
an attenuator is just

00:37:26.300 --> 00:37:27.345
attenuating a beam.

00:37:27.345 --> 00:37:31.050
An attenuator can always
regard it as a beam splitter.

00:37:31.050 --> 00:37:34.420
And you can do measurements at
both arms of the beam splitter.

00:37:34.420 --> 00:37:36.360
Or you have to consider
the vacuum noise which

00:37:36.360 --> 00:37:38.620
enters through the other
part of the beam splitter.

00:37:38.620 --> 00:37:44.580
And if you are now add that
those atoms, n atoms, in a trap

00:37:44.580 --> 00:37:47.050
have some natural loss
by inelastic collision

00:37:47.050 --> 00:37:49.670
or background gas
scattering, the loss

00:37:49.670 --> 00:37:53.110
is actually like a beam
splitter that particles

00:37:53.110 --> 00:37:56.280
don't stay in the trap, but
go out through the other part.

00:37:56.280 --> 00:37:58.070
And then you can measure it.

00:37:58.070 --> 00:38:01.400
So in other words,
every loss process

00:38:01.400 --> 00:38:03.836
should be regarded as
a possible measurement.

00:38:03.836 --> 00:38:05.210
And it doesn't
matter whether you

00:38:05.210 --> 00:38:08.240
perform the measurement or not.

00:38:08.240 --> 00:38:11.470
And I think it's just obvious
that the noon state, the moment

00:38:11.470 --> 00:38:15.920
one particle is lost and you
reduce this particle to figure

00:38:15.920 --> 00:38:19.410
out if n particles are here
or n particles are there,

00:38:19.410 --> 00:38:22.320
the whole superposition
state is lost if you just

00:38:22.320 --> 00:38:24.210
lose one single atom out of n.

00:38:28.970 --> 00:38:34.060
So the lifetime of a noon state
is then not your usual trap

00:38:34.060 --> 00:38:37.120
lifetime, where you
lose half of the atoms,

00:38:37.120 --> 00:38:38.660
1 over e of the atoms.

00:38:38.660 --> 00:38:42.280
It is n times faster because
it is the first atom lost,

00:38:42.280 --> 00:38:44.370
which is already
completely removing

00:38:44.370 --> 00:38:46.034
the entanglement of your state.

00:38:56.190 --> 00:39:00.450
So more quantitatively, to
say it more specifically,

00:39:00.450 --> 00:39:04.180
the limitation is loss.

00:39:04.180 --> 00:39:09.970
When you have a fully entangled
state, maximally entangled

00:39:09.970 --> 00:39:14.230
state, usually a
loss of one particle

00:39:14.230 --> 00:39:17.850
immediately removes
the entanglement.

00:39:17.850 --> 00:39:22.260
We had the situa-- no,
that's not a good example.

00:39:22.260 --> 00:39:26.060
But for the most
entangled state,

00:39:26.060 --> 00:39:27.840
usually-- and for
the noon state,

00:39:27.840 --> 00:39:31.820
it's trivial to see-- a
single particle lost allows

00:39:31.820 --> 00:39:35.560
you to measure on which side
of the potential barrier

00:39:35.560 --> 00:39:37.700
all the atoms are,
and all the beauty

00:39:37.700 --> 00:39:39.207
of the non-classical
state is lost.

00:39:42.870 --> 00:39:44.910
So if you assume that
in a time window,

00:39:44.910 --> 00:39:47.360
you have an infinitesimal
loss, a loss

00:39:47.360 --> 00:39:51.010
of epsilon, what
usually happens is

00:39:51.010 --> 00:39:53.730
if you have an entanglement
of n particles,

00:39:53.730 --> 00:39:56.330
then you lose your entanglement.

00:39:56.330 --> 00:39:58.820
If you expand 1
minus epsilon to n,

00:39:58.820 --> 00:40:02.470
it becomes 1 minus
n times epsilon.

00:40:02.470 --> 00:40:06.340
So that's one reason why
people have not scaled up

00:40:06.340 --> 00:40:09.160
those schemes to a
large number of photons,

00:40:09.160 --> 00:40:11.010
or a large number of atoms.

00:40:11.010 --> 00:40:14.060
Because the larger n
is, the more sensitive

00:40:14.060 --> 00:40:16.930
you are to even very,
very small losses.

00:40:26.630 --> 00:40:29.540
Questions?

00:40:29.540 --> 00:40:31.650
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:40:31.650 --> 00:40:32.275
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:40:32.275 --> 00:40:33.608
AUDIENCE: Or is that physically?

00:40:36.410 --> 00:40:38.910
PROFESSOR: The
super beam splitter

00:40:38.910 --> 00:40:42.580
would create the noon state.

00:40:42.580 --> 00:40:44.700
I've not explained to
you what it physically

00:40:44.700 --> 00:40:46.810
would be for photons,
but I gave you

00:40:46.810 --> 00:40:50.870
the example for atoms
to BECs in a double well

00:40:50.870 --> 00:40:53.540
potential with
attractive interaction.

00:40:53.540 --> 00:40:55.740
So to start with
the condensate in--

00:40:59.090 --> 00:41:00.840
AUDIENCE: Start with
a bigger [INAUDIBLE].

00:41:00.840 --> 00:41:03.200
PROFESSOR: If you start with
a double well potential,

00:41:03.200 --> 00:41:05.780
and you put in n
atoms initially in,

00:41:05.780 --> 00:41:10.030
but then you switch
on tunnel coupling,

00:41:10.030 --> 00:41:12.970
then you would
create the noon state

00:41:12.970 --> 00:41:15.040
if the interactions
are attractive,

00:41:15.040 --> 00:41:18.220
and if everything is idealized,
that you have a completely

00:41:18.220 --> 00:41:19.650
symmetric double well potential.

00:41:24.770 --> 00:41:31.336
OK, the last example is the
squeeze light Interferometer.

00:41:31.336 --> 00:41:33.250
I just want to
mention it briefly,

00:41:33.250 --> 00:41:35.880
because we've talked so
much about squeezed light.

00:41:35.880 --> 00:41:39.200
So now I want to show you
that squeezed light can also

00:41:39.200 --> 00:41:46.400
be used to realize Heisenberg
Limited Interferometery.

00:41:49.560 --> 00:41:57.520
So the idea is, when we plot
the electric field versus time,

00:41:57.520 --> 00:42:01.400
and if you do squeezing
in one quadrature,

00:42:01.400 --> 00:42:07.670
then for certain times,
the electric field

00:42:07.670 --> 00:42:09.770
has lower noise
and higher noise.

00:42:09.770 --> 00:42:11.130
We discussed that.

00:42:11.130 --> 00:42:15.090
And the idea is that if there is
no noise at the zero crossing,

00:42:15.090 --> 00:42:19.280
that this means we can determine
the zero crossing of the light,

00:42:19.280 --> 00:42:22.095
and therefore the phase
shift with higher accuracy.

00:42:27.130 --> 00:42:36.120
You may also argue if you
have this quasi-probabilities,

00:42:36.120 --> 00:42:45.260
and with squeezing, we have
squeezed the coherent light

00:42:45.260 --> 00:42:48.010
into an ellipse.

00:42:48.010 --> 00:43:01.070
And things propagate
with e to the i omega t.

00:43:01.070 --> 00:43:07.000
Then you can determine
a phase shift,

00:43:07.000 --> 00:43:10.370
which is sort of an angular
sector in this diagram,

00:43:10.370 --> 00:43:13.040
with higher precision
if you have squeezed

00:43:13.040 --> 00:43:16.890
this circle into an
ellipse like that.

00:43:16.890 --> 00:43:17.950
So that's the idea.

00:43:17.950 --> 00:43:24.780
And well, it's fairly clear that
squeezing, if done correctly,

00:43:24.780 --> 00:43:27.860
can provide a better
phase measurement.

00:43:27.860 --> 00:43:31.280
And what I want to show
you here in a few minutes

00:43:31.280 --> 00:43:36.040
is how you can think about it.

00:43:36.040 --> 00:43:40.500
So we have discussed at length
the optical Interferometer,

00:43:40.500 --> 00:43:44.440
where we have just a
coherence state at the input.

00:43:44.440 --> 00:43:47.360
This is your standard
laser Interferometer.

00:43:47.360 --> 00:43:51.880
But of course, very importantly,
the second input port

00:43:51.880 --> 00:43:53.120
has the vacuum state.

00:43:53.120 --> 00:43:55.540
And we discussed the
importance of that.

00:43:55.540 --> 00:43:57.920
So the one difference
we want to do now

00:43:57.920 --> 00:44:02.990
is that we replace the
vacuum at the second input

00:44:02.990 --> 00:44:06.540
by the squeezed
vacuum where r is

00:44:06.540 --> 00:44:09.200
the parameter of
the squeezed vacuum.

00:44:12.560 --> 00:44:14.660
OK, so that's pretty
much what we do.

00:44:14.660 --> 00:44:17.610
We take this state, we
plug it into our equation,

00:44:17.610 --> 00:44:19.340
we use exactly
the same formalism

00:44:19.340 --> 00:44:21.010
we have used for
coherence states.

00:44:21.010 --> 00:44:22.980
And the question,
what is the result?

00:44:22.980 --> 00:44:29.150
Well, the result will be that
the squeezing factor appears.

00:44:29.150 --> 00:44:38.560
Just as a reminder,
for our Interferometer,

00:44:38.560 --> 00:44:43.200
we derived the sensitivity
of the Interferometer.

00:44:43.200 --> 00:44:45.500
We had the quantities x and y.

00:44:45.500 --> 00:44:51.430
And the noise is delta in this
y operator squared divided by x.

00:44:51.430 --> 00:44:55.240
This was the result when we
operate the Interferometer

00:44:55.240 --> 00:44:58.050
at the phase shift
of 90 degrees.

00:44:58.050 --> 00:44:58.850
Just a reminder.

00:44:58.850 --> 00:45:00.010
That's what we have done.

00:45:00.010 --> 00:45:01.720
That's how we
analyze the situation

00:45:01.720 --> 00:45:02.795
with a coherent state.

00:45:05.770 --> 00:45:17.270
The signal x is
now-- the signal x

00:45:17.270 --> 00:45:22.475
is the number
measurement a dagger a.

00:45:26.480 --> 00:45:33.325
And we have now the input
of the coherent state.

00:45:37.120 --> 00:45:38.962
And b dagger b.

00:45:38.962 --> 00:45:41.340
We have an input
mode a and a mode b.

00:45:41.340 --> 00:45:42.480
They get split.

00:45:42.480 --> 00:45:44.370
And then we measure
it at the output.

00:45:44.370 --> 00:45:47.550
And we can now at the
output have photons--

00:45:47.550 --> 00:45:50.340
a dagger a, which come
from the coherent state,

00:45:50.340 --> 00:45:54.900
and b dagger b, which come
from the squeeze vacuum.

00:45:58.800 --> 00:46:03.410
So this is now using the
beam splitter formalism

00:46:03.410 --> 00:46:05.590
applied to the Interferometer.

00:46:05.590 --> 00:46:08.640
So this is now the
result we obtain.

00:46:08.640 --> 00:46:12.410
And in the strong local
oscillator approximation,

00:46:12.410 --> 00:46:16.790
it is only the first
part which contributes.

00:46:16.790 --> 00:46:20.550
And this is simply the number
or photons in the coherent beam.

00:46:23.810 --> 00:46:28.990
The expectation value
of y is 0, because it

00:46:28.990 --> 00:46:32.680
involves a b and
b dagger operator.

00:46:32.680 --> 00:46:40.310
And the squeezed
vacuum has only,

00:46:40.310 --> 00:46:43.400
if you write it down, in the
n basis, in the flux basis,

00:46:43.400 --> 00:46:44.920
has only even n.

00:46:44.920 --> 00:46:47.000
So if you change
n by one, you lose

00:46:47.000 --> 00:46:48.910
overlap with the
squeezed vacuum.

00:46:48.910 --> 00:46:52.480
So therefore, this
expectation value is 0.

00:46:52.480 --> 00:47:05.840
For the operator y squared,
you take this and square it.

00:47:05.840 --> 00:47:09.660
And you get many, many terms,
which I don't want to discuss.

00:47:09.660 --> 00:47:11.740
I use the strong
local oscillator.

00:47:11.740 --> 00:47:14.970
Limited a dagger and
a can be replaced

00:47:14.970 --> 00:47:18.660
by the eigenvalue alpha
of the coherent state.

00:47:18.660 --> 00:47:22.910
So therefore, I factor
out alpha squared

00:47:22.910 --> 00:47:29.570
in the strong local
oscillator limit.

00:47:29.570 --> 00:47:35.515
And then what is left is
b plus b dagger squared.

00:47:39.460 --> 00:47:44.900
And since we have
squeezed the vacuum,

00:47:44.900 --> 00:47:49.280
this gives us a factor
into the minus r.

00:47:49.280 --> 00:47:58.200
So if we put all those
results together,

00:47:58.200 --> 00:48:05.060
we find that the phase
uncertainty is now

00:48:05.060 --> 00:48:07.820
what we obtained when
we had a coherent state

00:48:07.820 --> 00:48:10.030
with the ordinary vacuum.

00:48:10.030 --> 00:48:12.460
And in the strong
local oscillator limit,

00:48:12.460 --> 00:48:15.050
the only difference
to the ordinary vacuum

00:48:15.050 --> 00:48:21.600
is that in this term, we've
got the exponential factor e

00:48:21.600 --> 00:48:25.780
to the minus r.

00:48:25.780 --> 00:48:27.770
And since we have
taken a square root,

00:48:27.770 --> 00:48:31.340
it's e to the minus r over 2.

00:48:31.340 --> 00:48:38.750
So that result would
actually suggest

00:48:38.750 --> 00:48:47.730
that the more we squeeze,
that delta phi should go to 0.

00:48:47.730 --> 00:48:50.430
So it seems even better
than the Heisenberg limit.

00:48:53.660 --> 00:48:59.460
However-- well, this is
too good to be true--

00:48:59.460 --> 00:49:02.310
what I've neglected here
is just the following.

00:49:02.310 --> 00:49:05.660
When you squeeze more
and more, the more you

00:49:05.660 --> 00:49:08.920
squeeze the vacuum,
the more photons

00:49:08.920 --> 00:49:12.250
are in the squeezed vacuum,
because this ellipse stitches

00:49:12.250 --> 00:49:15.880
further and further out and
has overlap with flux states

00:49:15.880 --> 00:49:18.230
at higher and higher
photon number.

00:49:18.230 --> 00:49:24.670
So therefore, when you go to
the limit of infinite squeezing,

00:49:24.670 --> 00:49:26.530
you squeeze out
of the limit where

00:49:26.530 --> 00:49:29.480
you can regard the local
oscillator as strong,

00:49:29.480 --> 00:49:31.530
because the squeezed
vacuum has more photons

00:49:31.530 --> 00:49:32.980
than your local oscillator.

00:49:32.980 --> 00:49:36.820
And then you have to
consider additional terms.

00:49:36.820 --> 00:49:39.070
So let me just write that down.

00:49:39.070 --> 00:49:52.620
However, the squeezed vacuum has
non-zero average photon number.

00:49:57.990 --> 00:50:00.670
And the photon number
of the squeezed vacuum

00:50:00.670 --> 00:50:06.880
is, of course, apply b dagger
b to the squeezed vacuum.

00:50:06.880 --> 00:50:11.730
This gives us a sinc function.

00:50:11.730 --> 00:50:14.480
And we can call this
the number of photons

00:50:14.480 --> 00:50:15.515
in the squeezed vacuum.

00:50:20.410 --> 00:50:26.880
So we have to consider now
this contribution to y square.

00:50:33.130 --> 00:50:36.770
So we have to
consider the quadrator

00:50:36.770 --> 00:50:39.620
of the ellipse, the long
part of the ellipse,

00:50:39.620 --> 00:50:42.390
the non-squeezed
quadrator component.

00:50:50.890 --> 00:50:52.910
And we have to
consider that when

00:50:52.910 --> 00:50:57.010
we calculate the expectation
value of y square.

00:50:57.010 --> 00:51:00.270
And then we find
additional terms,

00:51:00.270 --> 00:51:02.800
which I don't want
to derive here.

00:51:02.800 --> 00:51:06.886
And the question is then, if
you squeeze too much, you lose.

00:51:06.886 --> 00:51:08.635
So there's an optimal
amount of squeezing.

00:51:13.220 --> 00:51:19.290
And for this optimal
amount of squeezing,

00:51:19.290 --> 00:51:25.670
the phase uncertainty
becomes approximately one

00:51:25.670 --> 00:51:28.610
over the number of photons
in the coherent state,

00:51:28.610 --> 00:51:31.880
plus the number of photons
in your squeeze vacuum.

00:51:31.880 --> 00:51:35.345
So this is, again, very close
to the Heisenberg limit.

00:51:43.810 --> 00:51:46.560
So the situation
with squeezed light

00:51:46.560 --> 00:51:50.830
is less elegant, because
if you squeeze too much,

00:51:50.830 --> 00:51:52.510
you have to consider
additional terms.

00:51:52.510 --> 00:51:55.190
This is why I gave you the
example of the squeezed light

00:51:55.190 --> 00:51:56.690
and the squeezed
vacuum as the last.

00:51:56.690 --> 00:52:00.080
But again, the Heisenberg
limit is very fundamental

00:52:00.080 --> 00:52:01.190
as we discussed.

00:52:01.190 --> 00:52:03.710
And for an optimum
arrangement of the squeezing,

00:52:03.710 --> 00:52:06.830
you can also use a
squeezed vacuum input

00:52:06.830 --> 00:52:09.890
to the Interferometer to
realize the Heisenberg limit.

00:52:13.420 --> 00:52:14.823
Any questions?

00:52:22.320 --> 00:52:24.710
Why is squeezing important?

00:52:24.710 --> 00:52:29.350
Well, squeezing caught the
attention of the physics

00:52:29.350 --> 00:52:32.840
community when it was
suggested in connection

00:52:32.840 --> 00:52:35.080
with gravitational--
with the detection

00:52:35.080 --> 00:52:36.810
of gravitational waves.

00:52:36.810 --> 00:52:40.620
As you know, the
laser Interferometer,

00:52:40.620 --> 00:52:44.630
the most advanced one is
LIGO, has a monumental task

00:52:44.630 --> 00:52:47.290
in detecting a
very small signal.

00:52:47.290 --> 00:52:54.230
And pretty much everything which
precision metrology can provide

00:52:54.230 --> 00:52:56.870
is being implemented
for that purpose.

00:52:56.870 --> 00:53:00.230
So you can see, this is
like precision measurement.

00:53:00.230 --> 00:53:02.120
Like maybe the trip
to the moon was

00:53:02.120 --> 00:53:10.290
for aviation in
several decades ago.

00:53:10.290 --> 00:53:13.690
So everything is really--
a lot of things pushing

00:53:13.690 --> 00:53:15.430
the frontier of
precision measurement

00:53:15.430 --> 00:53:19.290
is motivated by the precision
needed for gravitational wave

00:53:19.290 --> 00:53:20.070
detection.

00:53:20.070 --> 00:53:27.110
And what I want to show
you here is a diagram

00:53:27.110 --> 00:53:29.240
for what is called
advanced LIGO.

00:53:29.240 --> 00:53:31.470
LIGO is currently
operating, but there

00:53:31.470 --> 00:53:34.500
is an upgrade to LIGO
called advanced LIGO.

00:53:34.500 --> 00:53:36.860
And what you
recognize here is we

00:53:36.860 --> 00:53:44.010
have a laser which goes into
a Michelson Interferometer.

00:53:44.010 --> 00:53:46.640
And this is how you want to
detect gravitational waves.

00:53:46.640 --> 00:53:50.030
But now you realize
that the addition here

00:53:50.030 --> 00:53:52.430
is a squeezed source.

00:53:52.430 --> 00:53:55.191
And what you are
squeezing is not,

00:53:55.191 --> 00:53:56.690
while it should be
clear to you now,

00:53:56.690 --> 00:53:58.680
we're not squeezing
the laser beam.

00:53:58.680 --> 00:54:01.470
This would be much, much harder,
because many, many photons are

00:54:01.470 --> 00:54:02.700
involved.

00:54:02.700 --> 00:54:10.360
But it is sufficient to
squeeze the vacuum and couple

00:54:10.360 --> 00:54:14.420
in squeezed vacuum into your
cavitational wave detector.

00:54:25.890 --> 00:54:29.300
If you wonder, it's a
little bit more complicated

00:54:29.300 --> 00:54:32.820
because people want to
recycle light and have

00:54:32.820 --> 00:54:35.650
put in other bells and whistles.

00:54:35.650 --> 00:54:38.590
But in essence, a
squeezed vacuum source

00:54:38.590 --> 00:54:41.950
is a major addition
to advanced LIGO.

00:54:41.950 --> 00:54:42.758
Yes.

00:54:42.758 --> 00:54:44.382
