00:55:44.920 --> 00:55:49.650
But high power lasers are
very important for keeping

00:55:49.650 --> 00:55:51.995
the classical short noise down.

00:55:51.995 --> 00:55:54.740
So you want to work with
the highest power possible.

00:55:54.740 --> 00:55:57.760
And therefore, you can't
allow the light to exit.

00:55:57.760 --> 00:55:59.040
You want to recycle it.

00:55:59.040 --> 00:56:01.450
You want to use
enhancement cavities.

00:56:01.450 --> 00:56:05.020
And what I can tell you is that
this set up here integrates,

00:56:05.020 --> 00:56:08.440
I think, the signal
recycling, the measurement

00:56:08.440 --> 00:56:09.790
at the zero fringe.

00:56:09.790 --> 00:56:12.000
And you see that kind
of those different parts

00:56:12.000 --> 00:56:14.320
are copied in a
way which I didn't

00:56:14.320 --> 00:56:17.090
prepare to explain it to you.

00:56:17.090 --> 00:56:19.660
All I wanted you to
do is pretty much

00:56:19.660 --> 00:56:23.410
recognize that a squeeze
light generator is important.

00:56:23.410 --> 00:56:25.660
And this enters
the interferometer

00:56:25.660 --> 00:56:27.130
as a squeezed vacuum.

00:56:34.230 --> 00:56:35.860
What I find very
interesting, and this

00:56:35.860 --> 00:56:38.640
is what I want to
discuss now is,

00:56:38.640 --> 00:56:42.120
that when you have an
interferometer like LIGO,

00:56:42.120 --> 00:56:45.080
cavitational wave
interferometer,

00:56:45.080 --> 00:56:48.380
and now you want to squeeze.

00:56:48.380 --> 00:56:50.150
Does it really help to squeeze?

00:56:50.150 --> 00:56:51.960
Does it always help to squeeze?

00:56:51.960 --> 00:56:54.780
Or what is the situation?

00:56:54.780 --> 00:56:56.750
And this is what I want
to discuss with you.

00:57:03.350 --> 00:57:11.440
So let's forget about signal
recycling and enhancement

00:57:11.440 --> 00:57:13.160
cavities and things like this.

00:57:13.160 --> 00:57:17.690
Let's just discuss the basic
cavitation wave detector, where

00:57:17.690 --> 00:57:20.440
we have an input,
we have the two arms

00:57:20.440 --> 00:57:22.480
of the Michelson interferometer.

00:57:22.480 --> 00:57:27.160
And to have more
sensitivity, the light

00:57:27.160 --> 00:57:30.310
bounces back and forth
in an enhancement cavity.

00:57:30.310 --> 00:57:33.100
You can say if the light bounces
back and forth 100 times,

00:57:33.100 --> 00:57:35.390
it is as if you had
an arm length which

00:57:35.390 --> 00:57:37.830
is 100 times larger.

00:57:37.830 --> 00:57:41.010
And now we put in
squeezed vacuum

00:57:41.010 --> 00:57:43.540
at the open part of
the interferometer.

00:57:43.540 --> 00:57:45.945
And here we have
our photo-diodes

00:57:45.945 --> 00:57:47.070
to perform the measurement.

00:57:53.190 --> 00:58:00.710
So the goal is to measure
a small length scale.

00:58:00.710 --> 00:58:03.680
If a cavitation wave comes
by, cavitational waves

00:58:03.680 --> 00:58:05.410
have quadrupolar character.

00:58:05.410 --> 00:58:07.970
So the metric will
be such that there's

00:58:07.970 --> 00:58:11.070
a quadrupolar perturbation
in the metric of space.

00:58:11.070 --> 00:58:16.090
And that means that, in
essence, one of the mirrors

00:58:16.090 --> 00:58:17.560
is slightly moving out.

00:58:17.560 --> 00:58:19.910
The other mirror is
slightly moving in.

00:58:19.910 --> 00:58:22.680
So therefore, the interferometer
needs a very, very high

00:58:22.680 --> 00:58:26.080
sensitivity to displacement
of one of the mirrors

00:58:26.080 --> 00:58:28.380
by an amount delta z.

00:58:28.380 --> 00:58:33.650
And if you normalize
delta z to the arm length,

00:58:33.650 --> 00:58:36.790
or the arm length times
the number of bounces,

00:58:36.790 --> 00:58:41.020
the task is to
measure sensitivity

00:58:41.020 --> 00:58:43.315
in a length displacement
of 10 to the minus 21.

00:58:46.350 --> 00:58:48.320
That's one of the
smallest numbers

00:58:48.320 --> 00:58:50.220
which have ever been measured.

00:58:50.220 --> 00:58:54.680
And therefore, it is clear
that this interferometer

00:58:54.680 --> 00:58:57.886
should operate as close
as possible to the quantum

00:58:57.886 --> 00:58:58.760
limit of measurement.

00:59:03.340 --> 00:59:06.880
So what you want to measure here
is, with the highest accuracy

00:59:06.880 --> 00:59:12.420
possible, the displacement
of an object delta z.

00:59:15.090 --> 00:59:21.050
However, your object fulfills
and uncertainty relationship,

00:59:21.050 --> 00:59:24.580
that if you want to measure
the position very accurately,

00:59:24.580 --> 00:59:31.020
you also have to consider that
it has a momentum uncertainty.

00:59:31.020 --> 00:59:34.020
And this fulfills Heisenberg's
uncertainty relation.

00:59:34.020 --> 00:59:37.460
You will say, well, why should
I care about the momentum

00:59:37.460 --> 00:59:41.740
uncertainty if all I want
to measure is the position.

00:59:41.740 --> 00:59:46.850
Well, you should care
because momentum uncertainty

00:59:46.850 --> 00:59:50.630
after a time tau turns
into position uncertainty,

00:59:50.630 --> 00:59:53.950
because position uncertainty
is uncertainty in velocity.

00:59:53.950 --> 00:59:56.120
And if I multiply
it by the time tau

00:59:56.120 --> 00:59:58.420
it takes you to perform
the measurement,

00:59:58.420 --> 01:00:00.890
you have now an
uncertainty in position,

01:00:00.890 --> 01:00:03.215
which comes from the original
uncertainty in momentum.

01:00:08.090 --> 01:00:13.040
So if I use the expression
for Heisenberg's Uncertainty

01:00:13.040 --> 01:00:17.130
Relation, I find this.

01:00:19.690 --> 01:00:24.170
And now, what we
have to minimize

01:00:24.170 --> 01:00:28.350
to get the highest precision
is the total uncertainty

01:00:28.350 --> 01:00:34.850
in position, which is
the original uncertainty,

01:00:34.850 --> 01:00:37.694
plus the uncertainty due
to the motion of the mirror

01:00:37.694 --> 01:00:38.985
during the measurement process.

01:00:43.040 --> 01:00:45.270
So what we have here
is we have delta z.

01:00:45.270 --> 01:00:48.320
We have a contribution which
scores as 1 over delta z.

01:00:48.320 --> 01:00:53.850
And by just finding out what is
the optimum choice of delta z,

01:00:53.850 --> 01:00:56.940
you find the result above.

01:00:56.940 --> 01:01:01.050
Or if you want to say you
want that this delta z tau is

01:01:01.050 --> 01:01:05.460
comparable to delta z, just
set this equal to delta z,

01:01:05.460 --> 01:01:12.510
solve for delta z, and
you find the quantum limit

01:01:12.510 --> 01:01:19.560
for the interferometer,
which is given up there.

01:01:19.560 --> 01:01:21.640
So this has nothing
to do with squeezing.

01:01:21.640 --> 01:01:25.340
And you cannot improve on this
quantum limit by squeezing.

01:01:25.340 --> 01:01:27.200
This is what you got.

01:01:27.200 --> 01:01:32.610
It only depends on the
duration of the measurement.

01:01:32.610 --> 01:01:35.696
And it depends on the
mass of the mirror.

01:01:41.410 --> 01:01:53.860
Now-- just get my
notes ready-- there

01:01:53.860 --> 01:01:57.880
is a very influential
and seminal paper

01:01:57.880 --> 01:02:00.400
by Caves-- the reference
is given here--

01:02:00.400 --> 01:02:03.000
which was really
laying out the concepts

01:02:03.000 --> 01:02:06.910
and the theory for quantum
limited measurements with such

01:02:06.910 --> 01:02:10.220
an interferometer, and
the use of squeezed light.

01:02:10.220 --> 01:02:15.420
Let me just summarize the
most important findings.

01:02:15.420 --> 01:02:20.150
So this paper explains that
you have two contributions

01:02:20.150 --> 01:02:27.760
to the noise, which
depend on the laser

01:02:27.760 --> 01:02:30.030
power you use for
your measurement.

01:02:30.030 --> 01:02:33.390
The first one is the
photon counting noise.

01:02:33.390 --> 01:02:36.870
If you use more and
more laser power,

01:02:36.870 --> 01:02:38.760
you have a better
and better signal,

01:02:38.760 --> 01:02:41.420
and your short noise is reduced.

01:02:41.420 --> 01:02:45.170
So therefore, you have a better
read out of the interferometer.

01:02:45.170 --> 01:02:46.970
And this is given here.

01:02:46.970 --> 01:02:51.240
Alpha is the eigenvalue
of the coherent state.

01:02:51.240 --> 01:02:54.810
But there is a second
aspect which you may not

01:02:54.810 --> 01:02:57.560
have thought about it,
and this is the following.

01:02:57.560 --> 01:03:02.140
If you split a laser
beam into two parts,

01:03:02.140 --> 01:03:04.060
you have fluctuations.

01:03:04.060 --> 01:03:09.350
The number of photons left
and right are not identical.

01:03:09.350 --> 01:03:11.420
You have a coherent
bean and you split it

01:03:11.420 --> 01:03:13.450
into two coherent
beams, and then you

01:03:13.450 --> 01:03:16.060
have Poissonian
fluctuations on either side.

01:03:16.060 --> 01:03:19.820
But if you have now Poissonian
fluctuations in the photon

01:03:19.820 --> 01:03:23.400
number, if those photons
are reflected off a mirror,

01:03:23.400 --> 01:03:26.510
they transfer photon
recoil to the mirror.

01:03:26.510 --> 01:03:32.860
And the mirror is pushed
by the radiation pressure.

01:03:32.860 --> 01:03:35.008
And it's pushed,
and it has-- there

01:03:35.008 --> 01:03:37.560
is a differential motion
of the two mirrors

01:03:37.560 --> 01:03:40.545
relative to each other due to
the fluctuations in the photon

01:03:40.545 --> 01:03:43.740
number in the two arms
of the interferometer.

01:03:43.740 --> 01:03:50.530
So therefore, what happens is
you have a delta z deviation

01:03:50.530 --> 01:03:55.580
or variance in the measurement
of the mirror, which

01:03:55.580 --> 01:03:57.930
comes from radiation pressure.

01:03:57.930 --> 01:04:01.970
It's a differential radiation
pressure between the two arms.

01:04:01.970 --> 01:04:06.860
And what Caves
showed in this paper

01:04:06.860 --> 01:04:10.520
is that the two effects
which contribute

01:04:10.520 --> 01:04:12.580
to the precision
of the measurement

01:04:12.580 --> 01:04:15.670
come from two different
quadrature component.

01:04:15.670 --> 01:04:18.770
For the photon
counting, we always

01:04:18.770 --> 01:04:21.900
want to squeeze the
light in such a way

01:04:21.900 --> 01:04:25.870
that we have the narrow
part of the ellipse

01:04:25.870 --> 01:04:31.880
in the quadrature component
of our coherent beam.

01:04:31.880 --> 01:04:33.960
We've discussed
it several times.

01:04:33.960 --> 01:04:39.340
So therefore, you want to
squeeze it by e to the minus r.

01:04:39.340 --> 01:04:45.190
However, when what has a good
effect for the photon counting

01:04:45.190 --> 01:04:47.092
has a bad effect
for the fluctuations

01:04:47.092 --> 01:04:48.175
due to radiation pressure.

01:04:59.850 --> 01:05:03.350
So therefore, what
happens is-- let's

01:05:03.350 --> 01:05:05.240
forget squeezing for a moment.

01:05:05.240 --> 01:05:10.440
If you have two contributions,
one goes to the noise,

01:05:10.440 --> 01:05:13.890
one goes with alpha squared
of the number of photons.

01:05:13.890 --> 01:05:16.820
One goes inverse with the square
root of the number of photons.

01:05:16.820 --> 01:05:20.390
You will find out that
even in the interferometer

01:05:20.390 --> 01:05:23.490
without squeezing, there
is an optimum laser

01:05:23.490 --> 01:05:25.630
power, which you want to use.

01:05:25.630 --> 01:05:28.100
Because if you use
two lower power,

01:05:28.100 --> 01:05:29.470
you lose in photon counting.

01:05:29.470 --> 01:05:31.570
If you use two higher
power, you lose

01:05:31.570 --> 01:05:35.600
in the fluctuations of
the radiation pressure.

01:05:35.600 --> 01:05:43.610
So even without squeezing,
there is an optimum laser power.

01:05:43.610 --> 01:05:48.900
And for typical parameters,
so there is an optimum power.

01:05:48.900 --> 01:05:52.020
And what we're
shown in this paper

01:05:52.020 --> 01:05:56.620
is whenever you choose
the optimum power which

01:05:56.620 --> 01:05:59.810
keeps a balance between
photon counting and radiation

01:05:59.810 --> 01:06:02.462
pressure, then you reach
the standard quantum

01:06:02.462 --> 01:06:03.670
limit of your interferometer.

01:06:06.760 --> 01:06:10.240
But it turns out that
for typical parameters,

01:06:10.240 --> 01:06:13.580
this optimum is 8,000 watt.

01:06:13.580 --> 01:06:15.960
So that's why
people at LIGO work

01:06:15.960 --> 01:06:18.840
harder and harder to develop
more and more powerful

01:06:18.840 --> 01:06:21.510
lasers, because more
laser power brings

01:06:21.510 --> 01:06:24.370
them closer and closer
to the optimum power.

01:06:24.370 --> 01:06:27.360
But once they had
the optimum power,

01:06:27.360 --> 01:06:29.730
additional squeezing
will not help them

01:06:29.730 --> 01:06:33.430
because they are already at
the fundamental quantum limit.

01:06:33.430 --> 01:06:38.090
So the one thing which
squeezing does for you, it

01:06:38.090 --> 01:06:42.420
changes the optimum
power in your input beam

01:06:42.420 --> 01:06:44.810
by a squeezing factor.

01:06:44.810 --> 01:06:47.320
So therefore, if you
have lasers which

01:06:47.320 --> 01:06:51.220
have maybe 100 watt
and not 8,000 watt,

01:06:51.220 --> 01:06:55.792
then squeezing helps you to
reach the fundamental quantum

01:06:55.792 --> 01:06:57.000
limit of your interferometer.

01:07:08.130 --> 01:07:10.680
So that's pretty
much all I wanted

01:07:10.680 --> 01:07:13.320
to say about precision
measurements.

01:07:13.320 --> 01:07:16.520
I hope the last example--
it's too complex to go

01:07:16.520 --> 01:07:19.170
through the whole analysis--
but it gives you at least a

01:07:19.170 --> 01:07:22.740
feel that you have
to keep your eye

01:07:22.740 --> 01:07:24.310
on both quadrature components.

01:07:24.310 --> 01:07:27.200
You can squeeze, you
can get an improvement,

01:07:27.200 --> 01:07:30.440
in one physical
effect, but you have

01:07:30.440 --> 01:07:34.020
to be careful to consider what
happens in the other quadrature

01:07:34.020 --> 01:07:34.724
component.

01:07:34.724 --> 01:07:37.140
And in the end, you have to
keep the two of them balanced.

01:07:42.430 --> 01:07:43.210
Any questions?

01:07:50.970 --> 01:07:51.470
Oops.

01:08:07.600 --> 01:08:09.100
OK.

01:08:09.100 --> 01:08:17.520
Well, we can get started with
a very short chapter, which

01:08:17.520 --> 01:08:27.180
is about g2.

01:08:27.180 --> 01:08:31.410
The g2 measurement
for light and atoms.

01:08:44.260 --> 01:08:51.750
I don't think you will
find the discussion I

01:08:51.750 --> 01:08:53.910
want to present to
you in any textbook.

01:08:53.910 --> 01:09:00.729
It is about whether g2 is 1 or
2, whether we have fluctuations

01:09:00.729 --> 01:09:01.899
or not.

01:09:01.899 --> 01:09:05.819
And the discussion will be
whether g2 of 2 and g2 of 1

01:09:05.819 --> 01:09:08.899
are quantum effect
or classical effects.

01:09:08.899 --> 01:09:16.810
So I want to give you
here in this discussion

01:09:16.810 --> 01:09:21.920
four different derivations of
whether g2 is 1 or g2 is 2.

01:09:21.920 --> 01:09:23.649
And they look very,
very different.

01:09:23.649 --> 01:09:25.370
Some are based on
classical physics.

01:09:25.370 --> 01:09:28.420
Some are based on the
concept of interference.

01:09:28.420 --> 01:09:31.270
And some are based on the
quantum indistinguishability

01:09:31.270 --> 01:09:33.270
of particles.

01:09:33.270 --> 01:09:36.869
And once you see you all those
four different explanations,

01:09:36.869 --> 01:09:38.410
I think you'll see
the whole picture.

01:09:38.410 --> 01:09:41.680
And I hope you
understand something.

01:09:41.680 --> 01:09:45.430
So again, it's a long
story about factors of 2.

01:09:45.430 --> 01:09:49.020
But there are some factors of 2
which are purely calculational,

01:09:49.020 --> 01:09:51.060
and there are other
factors of 2 which

01:09:51.060 --> 01:09:53.779
involve a hell of
a lot of physics.

01:09:53.779 --> 01:09:56.740
I mean, there are people
who say the g2 factor of 2

01:09:56.740 --> 01:10:00.210
is really the difference between
ordinary light and laser light.

01:10:00.210 --> 01:10:03.390
For light from a
light bulb, g2 is 2.

01:10:03.390 --> 01:10:05.550
For light from a laser, g2 is 1.

01:10:05.550 --> 01:10:07.590
And this is the only
fundamental difference

01:10:07.590 --> 01:10:09.410
between laser light
and ordinary light.

01:10:09.410 --> 01:10:12.460
So this factor of
2 is important.

01:10:12.460 --> 01:10:19.890
And I want to therefore have
this additional discussion

01:10:19.890 --> 01:10:20.745
of the g2 function.

01:10:23.380 --> 01:10:32.390
So let me remind
you that g2 of 0

01:10:32.390 --> 01:10:45.900
is the normalized probability
to detect two photons or two

01:10:45.900 --> 01:10:52.770
particles simultaneously.

01:11:01.300 --> 01:11:16.140
And so far, we have
discussed it for light.

01:11:16.140 --> 01:11:21.205
And the result we obtained by
using our quantum formulation

01:11:21.205 --> 01:11:26.400
of light with creation
annihilation operator,

01:11:26.400 --> 01:11:31.480
we found that g2 is 0.

01:11:31.480 --> 01:11:36.810
In the situation that we had
black body radiation, which

01:11:36.810 --> 01:11:41.950
we can call thermal
light, it's sometimes

01:11:41.950 --> 01:11:45.020
goes by the name chaotic light.

01:11:45.020 --> 01:11:47.190
Sometimes it's called
classical light,

01:11:47.190 --> 01:11:50.350
but that may be a misnomer,
because I regard the laser

01:11:50.350 --> 01:11:52.930
beam as a very
classical form of light.

01:11:56.580 --> 01:11:59.340
This is sometimes
called bunching

01:11:59.340 --> 01:12:01.270
because 2 is larger than 1.

01:12:01.270 --> 01:12:03.780
So pairs of photons
appear bunched up.

01:12:03.780 --> 01:12:07.310
You have a higher probability
than you would naively

01:12:07.310 --> 01:12:12.270
expect of detecting two
photons simultaneously.

01:12:12.270 --> 01:12:19.670
And then we had the situation of
laser light and coherent light

01:12:19.670 --> 01:12:24.240
where the g2 function was 1.

01:12:24.240 --> 01:12:28.660
And I want to shed some
light on those two cases.

01:12:28.660 --> 01:12:35.640
We have discussed the extreme
case of a single photon

01:12:35.640 --> 01:12:38.430
where the probability
of detecting two photons

01:12:38.430 --> 01:12:40.040
is 0 for trivial reasons.

01:12:40.040 --> 01:12:42.662
So you have a g2 function of 0.

01:12:45.760 --> 01:12:47.930
But this is not what I
want to discuss here.

01:12:47.930 --> 01:12:51.570
I want to shed some
light on when do we

01:12:51.570 --> 01:12:53.720
get a g2 function of 1.

01:12:53.720 --> 01:12:56.800
When do we get a
g2 function of 2.

01:12:56.800 --> 01:13:04.010
And one question
we want to address,

01:13:04.010 --> 01:13:09.560
when we have a g2
function of 2, is

01:13:09.560 --> 01:13:19.790
this a classical
or quantum effect?

01:13:28.320 --> 01:13:31.010
Do you have an opinion?

01:13:31.010 --> 01:13:32.133
Who thinks-- question.

01:13:32.133 --> 01:13:34.133
AUDIENCE: When we did the
homework problem where

01:13:34.133 --> 01:13:35.930
we had the linear's
position, like alpha

01:13:35.930 --> 01:13:38.870
minus alpha
[INAUDIBLE] plus alpha,

01:13:38.870 --> 01:13:41.810
we found that one can
have a g2 greater than 1,

01:13:41.810 --> 01:13:43.770
and one can have
a g2 less than 1.

01:13:43.770 --> 01:13:46.710
So maybe g2 isn't a
great discriminator,

01:13:46.710 --> 01:13:49.160
whether it's very
quantum or very classic.

01:13:53.017 --> 01:13:54.725
PROFESSOR: Let's hold
this thought, yeah.

01:13:54.725 --> 01:13:55.830
You may be right.

01:14:00.920 --> 01:14:03.430
Let's come back to that.

01:14:03.430 --> 01:14:06.580
I think that's one opinion.

01:14:06.580 --> 01:14:09.700
The g2 function may
not be a discriminator,

01:14:09.700 --> 01:14:14.070
because we can have g2 of 1
and g2 of 2 purely classical.

01:14:14.070 --> 01:14:18.350
But why classical light
behaves classically,

01:14:18.350 --> 01:14:21.200
maybe that's what we
can understand there.

01:14:21.200 --> 01:14:22.670
And maybe what I
want to tell you

01:14:22.670 --> 01:14:27.490
is that a lot of classical
properties of classical light

01:14:27.490 --> 01:14:31.110
can be traced down to the
indistinguishability of bosons,

01:14:31.110 --> 01:14:33.020
which are photons.

01:14:33.020 --> 01:14:35.610
So in other words, we
shouldn't be surprised

01:14:35.610 --> 01:14:38.340
that something which
seems purely classical

01:14:38.340 --> 01:14:41.090
is deeply rooted
in quantum physics.

01:14:41.090 --> 01:14:44.290
But I'm ahead of my agenda.

01:14:44.290 --> 01:14:46.390
So let me start now.

01:14:46.390 --> 01:14:48.510
I want to offer you
four different views.

01:14:59.440 --> 01:15:05.034
And the first one is that
we have random intensity

01:15:05.034 --> 01:15:05.575
fluctuations.

01:15:08.230 --> 01:15:09.960
Think of a classical
light source.

01:15:15.790 --> 01:15:20.450
And we assume that if
things are really random,

01:15:20.450 --> 01:15:22.590
they are described by a
Gaussian distribution.

01:15:25.650 --> 01:15:28.930
And if you switch on
a light bulb, what

01:15:28.930 --> 01:15:31.920
you get if you measure the
intensity when you measure what

01:15:31.920 --> 01:15:36.290
is the probability that the
momentary intensity is I,

01:15:36.290 --> 01:15:40.240
well, you have to normalize
it to the average intensity.

01:15:40.240 --> 01:15:47.890
But what you get is pretty much
an exponential distribution.

01:15:47.890 --> 01:15:49.610
And this exponential
distribution

01:15:49.610 --> 01:15:51.980
has a maximum at I equals 0.

01:15:51.980 --> 01:15:55.790
So the most probable
intensity of all intensities

01:15:55.790 --> 01:15:57.420
when you switch
on a light bulb is

01:15:57.420 --> 01:16:00.210
that you have 0 intensity
at a given moment.

01:16:00.210 --> 01:16:06.140
But the average
intensity is I average.

01:16:06.140 --> 01:16:12.550
So you can easily, for
such a distribution,

01:16:12.550 --> 01:16:14.350
for such an exponential
distribution,

01:16:14.350 --> 01:16:18.710
figure out what is the
average of I to the power n.

01:16:18.710 --> 01:16:22.000
It is related to I
average to the power n,

01:16:22.000 --> 01:16:25.060
but it has an n factorial.

01:16:25.060 --> 01:16:28.730
And what is important is the
case for our discussion of n

01:16:28.730 --> 01:16:32.770
equals 2, where the
square of the intensity

01:16:32.770 --> 01:16:36.850
averaged is two times the
average intensity squared.

01:16:39.700 --> 01:16:44.120
And classically, g2
is the probability

01:16:44.120 --> 01:16:46.900
of detecting two
photons simultaneously,

01:16:46.900 --> 01:16:49.990
which is proportional
to I square.

01:16:49.990 --> 01:16:51.230
We have to normalize it.

01:16:51.230 --> 01:16:54.220
And we normalize it
by I average square.

01:16:54.220 --> 01:16:56.940
And this gives 2.

01:16:56.940 --> 01:17:01.910
So simply light with
Gaussian fluctuations

01:17:01.910 --> 01:17:06.630
would give rise to
a g2 function of 2.

01:17:06.630 --> 01:17:10.800
Since it's random fluctuations,
it's also called chaotic light.

01:17:10.800 --> 01:17:13.780
And the physical pictures
is the following.

01:17:13.780 --> 01:17:19.350
If you detect a photon,
the light is fluctuating.

01:17:19.350 --> 01:17:22.440
But whenever you detect
the first photon,

01:17:22.440 --> 01:17:25.440
it is more probable that you
detect take the first photon

01:17:25.440 --> 01:17:28.490
when the intensity
happened to be high.

01:17:28.490 --> 01:17:30.760
And then since the
intensity is high,

01:17:30.760 --> 01:17:32.720
the probability
for the next photon

01:17:32.720 --> 01:17:34.390
is higher than the
average probability.

01:17:38.240 --> 01:17:43.340
So therefore, you get
necessarily a g2 function of 2.

01:17:43.340 --> 01:17:44.560
So this is the physics of it.

01:17:47.140 --> 01:17:50.040
So let me just write that down.

01:17:50.040 --> 01:18:07.800
The first photon is more
likely to be detected

01:18:07.800 --> 01:18:19.400
when the intensity
fluctuation-- when

01:18:19.400 --> 01:18:21.720
intensity fluctuations
give high intensity.

01:18:26.820 --> 01:18:29.330
And then we get this result.

01:18:40.950 --> 01:18:42.780
Yes.

01:18:42.780 --> 01:18:48.350
Let us discuss a second
classical view, which

01:18:48.350 --> 01:18:50.690
I can call wave interference.

01:18:58.500 --> 01:18:59.610
This is really important.

01:18:59.610 --> 01:19:01.890
A lot of people get
confused about it.

01:19:01.890 --> 01:19:07.120
If you have light
in only one mode,

01:19:07.120 --> 01:19:10.550
this would be the
laser of, for atoms,

01:19:10.550 --> 01:19:11.935
the Bose-Einstein condensate.

01:19:15.430 --> 01:19:19.310
One mode means a single wave.

01:19:19.310 --> 01:19:24.470
So if we have plain waves, we
can describe all the photons

01:19:24.470 --> 01:19:26.350
or all the atoms by
this wave function.

01:19:29.330 --> 01:19:31.910
So what is the g2 function
for an object like this?

01:19:35.350 --> 01:19:35.850
AUDIENCE: 1.

01:19:35.850 --> 01:19:39.920
PROFESSOR: Trivially
1, because if something

01:19:39.920 --> 01:19:48.835
is a clean wave, a single
wave, all correlation functions

01:19:48.835 --> 01:19:49.335
factorize.

01:19:54.600 --> 01:20:00.140
You have the situation that
I to the power n average

01:20:00.140 --> 01:20:03.230
is I average to the power n.

01:20:03.230 --> 01:20:08.570
And that means that
gn is 1 for all n.

01:20:13.670 --> 01:20:19.850
OK, but let's now
assume that we have two.

01:20:19.850 --> 01:20:23.000
We can also use more, but
I want to restrict to two.

01:20:23.000 --> 01:20:25.840
That we have only two modes.

01:20:25.840 --> 01:20:29.170
And two modes can interfere.

01:20:29.170 --> 01:20:35.550
So let me apply to those
two modes a simple model.

01:20:35.550 --> 01:20:39.650
And whether it's simple
or not is relative.

01:20:39.650 --> 01:20:42.070
So it goes like as follows.

01:20:42.070 --> 01:20:49.990
If you have two modes,
both of Unity intensity,

01:20:49.990 --> 01:20:53.430
then the average intensity is 2.

01:20:57.920 --> 01:21:09.430
But if you have interference,
then the normalized intensity

01:21:09.430 --> 01:21:13.450
will vary between 0 and 4.

01:21:13.450 --> 01:21:16.040
Constructive interference
means you get twice as much

01:21:16.040 --> 01:21:16.650
as average.

01:21:16.650 --> 01:21:19.640
Destructive means
you get nothing.

01:21:19.640 --> 01:21:22.380
So therefore, the
[? nt ?] squared

01:21:22.380 --> 01:21:30.300
will vary between 0 and 16.

01:21:30.300 --> 01:21:33.940
So if I just use the two
extremes, it works out well.

01:21:33.940 --> 01:21:36.830
You have an I
square, which is 8,

01:21:36.830 --> 01:21:39.110
the average of
constructive interference

01:21:39.110 --> 01:21:41.370
and destructive interference.

01:21:41.370 --> 01:21:44.900
And this is two times
the average intensity,

01:21:44.900 --> 01:21:48.220
which is 2 squared.

01:21:48.220 --> 01:21:52.400
So therefore, if you
simply allow fluctuations

01:21:52.400 --> 01:21:54.860
due to the interference
of two modes,

01:21:54.860 --> 01:21:57.960
we find that the
g2 function is 2.

01:22:00.550 --> 01:22:13.280
So this demonstrates
that g2 of 2

01:22:13.280 --> 01:22:18.875
has its deep origin
in wave interference.

01:22:27.890 --> 01:22:34.230
And indeed, if you take a
light bulb which emits photons,

01:22:34.230 --> 01:22:37.760
you have many, many atoms
in your tungsten filament

01:22:37.760 --> 01:22:40.620
which can emit, re-emit waves.

01:22:40.620 --> 01:22:42.760
And since they have
different positions,

01:22:42.760 --> 01:22:46.790
the waves arrive at your
detector with random phases.

01:22:46.790 --> 01:22:49.290
And if you really write
that down in a model--

01:22:49.290 --> 01:22:51.540
this is nicely done in
the book by Loudon--

01:22:51.540 --> 01:22:54.390
you realize that
random interference

01:22:54.390 --> 01:22:58.590
between waves results in
an exponential distribution

01:22:58.590 --> 01:23:00.600
of intensity.

01:23:00.600 --> 01:23:02.700
So most people wouldn't
make the connection.

01:23:02.700 --> 01:23:06.050
But there is a deep and
fundamental relationship

01:23:06.050 --> 01:23:11.270
between random interference and
the most random distribution,

01:23:11.270 --> 01:23:13.780
the exponential
distribution, intensity

01:23:13.780 --> 01:23:18.700
which characterises thermal
light or chaotic light.

01:23:22.330 --> 01:23:25.380
So let me just write that down.

01:23:25.380 --> 01:23:34.680
So the Gaussian intensity
distribution-- actually

01:23:34.680 --> 01:23:39.350
it's an exponential
intensity distribution.

01:23:39.350 --> 01:23:41.290
But if you write the
intensity distribution

01:23:41.290 --> 01:23:43.280
as a distribution in
the electric field,

01:23:43.280 --> 01:23:44.910
intensity becomes e square.

01:23:44.910 --> 01:23:46.850
Then it becomes a
Gaussian [INAUDIBLE].

01:23:46.850 --> 01:23:50.650
So Gaussian or exponential
intensity distribution

01:23:50.650 --> 01:23:57.130
in view number one is the
result, is indeed the result,

01:23:57.130 --> 01:23:59.055
of interference.

01:24:02.890 --> 01:24:05.110
Any questions?

01:24:05.110 --> 01:24:06.656
So these are the
two classical views.

